pd.set_option('display.max_columns',None)
df1.head()Life expectancy is the estimated average number of years a person is expected to live based on various demographic, health, and economic factors. The factors you listed play a significant role in determining life expectancy: Factors Affecting Life Expectancy: 1. Country & Year: o Different countries have varying life expectancy rates due to differences in healthcare, nutrition, and living standards. o Over time, improvements in medicine and living conditions can increase life expectancy. 2. Status: o This could refer to developed, developing, or underdeveloped countries, where developed nations typically have higher life expectancy. 3. Life Expectancy: o The actual number of years a person is expected to live based on available data. 4. Adult Mortality Rate: o The probability of adults dying before reaching old age. Higher adult mortality lowers life expectancy. 5. Infant Deaths & Under-Five Deaths: o High infant mortality (death of babies before age 1) and under-five mortality (death before age 5) indicate poor healthcare, reducing overall life expectancy. 6. Alcohol Consumption: o High alcohol consumption is linked to diseases like liver failure, heart disease, and accidents, which can lower life expectancy. 7. Healthcare Expenditure (Percentage of GDP & Total Expenditure): o Countries that invest more in healthcare typically have higher life expectancy. 8. Hepatitis B & Measles Immunization Rates: o Higher vaccination rates reduce life-threatening diseases, increasing life expectancy. 9. BMI (Body Mass Index): o Both obesity and malnutrition (thinness 1-19 years, thinness 5-9 years) impact life expectancy by increasing risks for diseases. 10. Polio & Diphtheria Vaccination: Widespread vaccination programs improve child survival rates, positively impacting life expectancy. 11. HIV/AIDS Prevalence: High HIV/AIDS infection rates reduce life expectancy, especially in countries with limited treatment options. 12. GDP (Gross Domestic Product): Higher GDP generally leads to better healthcare, education, and nutrition, increasing life expectancy. 13. Population Size: Large populations in developing countries may struggle with healthcare and resources, affecting life expectancy. 14. Income Composition of Resources: Represents how well economic resources are distributed. Higher income equality leads to better health access, increasing life expectancy. 15. Schooling (Years of Education): Higher education levels improve awareness about hygiene, nutrition, and health, leading to a longer life expectancy.

def fill_null_value(df1):
  for col in df1.columns:
    if df1[col].dtype=='O':
      mode_value=df1[col].mode()[0]
      df1[col].fillna(mode_value,inplace=True)
    else:
      mean_value=df1[col].mean()
      median_value=df1[col].median()

      if abs(mean_value-median_value)<5:
        df1[col].fillna(mean_value,inplace=True)
      else:
        df1[col].fillna(median_value,inplace=True)
  return df1

df1=fill_null_value(df1)
